==English==

===Etymology 1===
The origin is not known with certainty, although first attested in 1775 CE in British criminals' slang[http://www.etymonline.com/index.php?search=fake&searchmode=none].  It is probably from ''[[feague]]'', "to give a better appearence through artificial means"; from the German ''[[fegen]]'', "to sweep", "to polish".

===Pronunciation===
*{{AHD|/fāk/}}
*{{audio|en-us-fake.ogg|Audio (US)}}

===Adjective===
'''fake'''
# not real; [[false]], [[fraudulent]]

===Noun===
'''fake'''  (''plural:'' '''[[fakes]]''')
# a [[trick]]; a [[swindle]]
# something which is not genuine, or is presented fraudulently

===Verb===
{{en-verb|fak|ing}}

# To cheat; to swindle; to steal; to rob.
# To make; to construct; to do.
# To manipulate fraudulently, so as to make an object appear better or other than it really is; as, to fake a bulldog, by burning his upper lip and thus artificially shortening it.

===Etymology 2===
From Middle English ''faken'', ''to coil a rope''.

===Noun===
'''fake'''  (''plural:'' '''[[fakes]]''')
# One of the circles or windings of a cable or hawser, as it lies in a coil; a single turn or coil.

===Verb===
{{en-verb|fak|ing}}

# To coil (a rope, line, or hawser), by winding alternately in opposite directions, in layers usually of zigzag or figure of eight form, to prevent twisting when running out.

